article.description: Tina Thompson and the Houston Comets earned  a measure of revenge.
article.headline: Thompson hits four 3-pointers
article.linkText: Thompson sparks Comets' win over Monarchs
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Tina Thompson's big game helped the Houston
Comets end another May with a winning record.

Thompson scored 27 points, including a perfect 4-of-4 from
3-point range, to lead the Comets to a 63-57 victory over the
Sacramento Monarchs on Sunday.

Thompson got Houston going with eight points in the first eight
minutes, then put the Comets on top to stay with her final
3-pointer with 5:07 left.

The victory allowed the Comets (3-2) to avoid their first losing
record in the month of May in franchise history.

"It's a win, we needed it," Thompson said.

Kendra Holland-Corn added 12 points and some big defensive stops
for the Comets after struggling with her shot during the Comets'
first four games.

"It is very important for me to come out offensively minded
because this team needs one more person to be offensively minded,"
Holland-Corn said.

Ruthie Bolton provided a lift off the bench for Sacramento with
13 points in the first half while star center Yolanda Griffith was
held scoreless.

"We were struggling offensively, and I just wanted to come in
and be a spark," Bolton said.

Griffith played a strong second half, but the Comets held Bolton
scoreless for the rest of the game.

"I think Ruthie is the heart of their offense as Yolanda
Griffith is the heart of their defense," Thompson said. "Ruthie
came in and she was on fire. That was definitely our focus going
into the second half."

Griffith finished with nine points and eight rebounds, and Kara
Lawson added nine points including a 3-pointer in the last minute
to pull the Monarchs within three.

Griffith tied the score at 45 with 9:44 left, but the Comets
closed out the win with an 18-12 run.

"We should have got this game," Griffith said. "We just have
to learn from it and get ready for the next game. It's frustrating,
but when we tie the game up, we've got to have that killer
instinct."
